          "id": "medquad-chunk-1799843bc525a8c8",
          "title": "Is Aarskog-Scott syndrome inherited ?",
          "content": "Aarskog-Scott syndrome is a genetic condition that is inherited through a pattern known as X-linked recessive inheritance. This means that the gene responsible for this syndrome is found on the X chromosome, which is one of the two types of sex chromosomes that determine an individual's sex. In males, who have only one X chromosome, the presence of just one altered copy of the gene in each cell is enough to cause the syndrome. This is because males have only one X chromosome, so if that one is affected, they will express the condition. On the other hand, females have two X chromosomes. For a female to be affected by Aarskog-Scott syndrome, both copies of the gene would need to be altered. This makes it much less likely for females to be affected by this condition compared to males. As a result, boys are diagnosed with X-linked recessive disorders like Aarskog-Scott syndrome much more frequently than girls.\nInterestingly, females who carry one altered copy of the FGD1 gene, which is associated with Aarskog-Scott syndrome, may exhibit mild signs of the condition. These signs can include features such as widely spaced eyes, shorter stature than average, or a widow's peak hairline. It is important to note that a unique aspect of X-linked inheritance is that fathers cannot pass X-linked traits to their sons. This is because sons inherit their Y chromosome from their fathers, which means they receive their X chromosome from their mothers. Understanding this pattern of inheritance is crucial for families as they learn about the transmission of Aarskog-Scott syndrome and its implications for family planning and genetic counseling. By recognizing how this condition is passed down through generations, families can make informed decisions and seek appropriate medical advice if needed.\nContext recap: Aarskog-Scott syndrome is a genetic condition that is inherited through a pattern known as X-linked recessive inheritance. This means that the gene responsible for this syndrome is found on the X chromosome, which is one of the two types of sex chromosomes that determine an individual's sex. In males, who have only one X chromosome, the presence of just one altered copy of the gene in each cell is enough to cause the syndrome. This is because males have only one X chromosome, so if that one is affected, they will express the condition.\nWhy this matters: Is Aarskog-Scott syndrome inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Aarskog-Scott syndrome is a genetic condition that is inherited through a pattern known as X-linked recessive inheritance. This means that the gene responsible for this syndrome is found on the X chromosome, which is one of the two types of sex chromosomes that determine an individual's sex. In males, who have only one X chromosome, the presence of just one altered copy of the gene in each cell is enough to cause the syndrome. This is because males have only one X chromosome, so if that one is affected, they will express the condition.\nWhy this matters: Is Aarskog-Scott syndrome inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
