          "id": "medquad-chunk-672c40de157e9bf9",
          "title": "How many people are affected by abdominal wall defect ?",
          "content": "Abdominal wall defects are relatively rare conditions that can affect newborns. One type of defect, called omphalocele, occurs in about 2 to 2.5 out of every 10,000 newborns. This means that for every 10,000 babies born, only about 2 to 2.5 will have this specific condition. Another type, known as gastroschisis, is a bit more common, affecting approximately 2 to 6 out of every 10,000 newborns. Interestingly, researchers have observed that the occurrence of gastroschisis seems to be on the rise, which is an important trend to monitor. It's also noteworthy that abdominal wall defects are more frequently seen in pregnancies that do not go to full term, such as those that result in miscarriages or stillbirths. By understanding how often these conditions occur, we can work towards raising awareness and improving the quality of prenatal care for expectant parents. This knowledge is crucial for healthcare providers to better support families and ensure healthier outcomes for both mothers and their babies.\nContext recap: Abdominal wall defects are relatively rare conditions that can affect newborns. One type of defect, called omphalocele, occurs in about 2 to 2.5 out of every 10,000 newborns. This means that for every 10,000 babies born, only about 2 to 2.5 will have this specific condition. Another type, known as gastroschisis, is a bit more common, affecting approximately 2 to 6 out of every 10,000 newborns.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by abdominal wall defect ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Abdominal wall defects are relatively rare conditions that can affect newborns. One type of defect, called omphalocele, occurs in about 2 to 2.5 out of every 10,000 newborns. This means that for every 10,000 babies born, only about 2 to 2.5 will have this specific condition. Another type, known as gastroschisis, is a bit more common, affecting approximately 2 to 6 out of every 10,000 newborns.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by abdominal wall defect ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Abdominal wall defects are relatively rare conditions that can affect newborns. One type of defect, called omphalocele, occurs in about 2 to 2.5 out of every 10,000 newborns. This means that for every 10,000 babies born, only about 2 to 2.5 will have this specific condition. Another type, known as gastroschisis, is a bit more common, affecting approximately 2 to 6 out of every 10,000 newborns.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by abdominal wall defect ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
