          "title": "How many people are affected by abetalipoproteinemia ?",
          "content": "Abetalipoproteinemia is a very rare genetic disorder, with only about 100 cases reported worldwide. This rarity makes it a unique condition that requires specialized knowledge and understanding. Awareness of such rare disorders is important for healthcare professionals and researchers, as it can lead to better diagnosis and treatment options for affected individuals.\nContext recap: Abetalipoproteinemia is a very rare genetic disorder, with only about 100 cases reported worldwide. This rarity makes it a unique condition that requires specialized knowledge and understanding. Awareness of such rare disorders is important for healthcare professionals and researchers, as it can lead to better diagnosis and treatment options for affected individuals.\nContext recap: Abetalipoproteinemia is a very rare genetic disorder, with only about 100 cases reported worldwide. This rarity makes it a unique condition that requires specialized knowledge and understanding. Awareness of such rare disorders is important for healthcare professionals and researchers, as it can lead to better diagnosis and treatment options for affected individuals. Context recap: Abetalipoproteinemia is a very rare genetic disorder, with only about 100 cases reported worldwide.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by abetalipoproteinemia ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Abetalipoproteinemia is a very rare genetic disorder, with only about 100 cases reported worldwide. This rarity makes it a unique condition that requires specialized knowledge and understanding. Awareness of such rare disorders is important for healthcare professionals and researchers, as it can lead to better diagnosis and treatment options for affected individuals. Context recap: Abetalipoproteinemia is a very rare genetic disorder, with only about 100 cases reported worldwide.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by abetalipoproteinemia ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
