          "id": "medquad-chunk-13e9be17fe3f6327",
          "title": "How many people are affected by acatalasemia ?",
          "content": "Acatalasemia is a very rare genetic condition, and so far, more than 100 cases have been documented in medical literature. This means that only a small number of people have been identified with this condition. Researchers have made estimates about how common acatalasemia is in different countries. For instance, in Japan, it is estimated that about 1 in every 12,500 people may have acatalasemia. In Hungary, the estimate is about 1 in every 20,000 people, while in Switzerland, it is approximately 1 in every 25,000 people. These numbers indicate that acatalasemia is not very common, but it is important to note that the prevalence of this condition in other populations around the world is still largely unknown. More research is needed to gather accurate data on how many people are affected globally. Understanding how acatalasemia is distributed across different regions can help researchers and healthcare providers develop better support systems for individuals living with this condition, ensuring they receive the care and attention they need.\nContext recap: Acatalasemia is a very rare genetic condition, and so far, more than 100 cases have been documented in medical literature. This means that only a small number of people have been identified with this condition. Researchers have made estimates about how common acatalasemia is in different countries. For instance, in Japan, it is estimated that about 1 in every 12,500 people may have acatalasemia.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by acatalasemia ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Acatalasemia is a very rare genetic condition, and so far, more than 100 cases have been documented in medical literature. This means that only a small number of people have been identified with this condition. Researchers have made estimates about how common acatalasemia is in different countries. For instance, in Japan, it is estimated that about 1 in every 12,500 people may have acatalasemia.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by acatalasemia ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: Acatalasemia is a very rare genetic condition, and so far, more than 100 cases have been documented in medical literature. This means that only a small number of people have been identified with this condition. Researchers have made estimates about how common acatalasemia is in different countries. For instance, in Japan, it is estimated that about 1 in every 12,500 people may have acatalasemia.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by acatalasemia ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
