          "id": "medquad-chunk-2499747ba13c121f",
          "title": "How many people are affected by achromatopsia ?",
          "content": "Achromatopsia is a rare visual condition that affects approximately 1 in every 30,000 individuals worldwide. This means that for every 30,000 people, one person may experience this condition, which can significantly impact their ability to see colors. Among those who have achromatopsia, complete achromatopsia, where individuals cannot perceive any colors at all, is more commonly seen than incomplete achromatopsia, where some color vision may still be present. A fascinating aspect of this condition is its higher prevalence among the Pingelapese islanders, a group of people living on one of the Eastern Caroline Islands in Micronesia. In this specific population, research indicates that between 4 and 10 percent of individuals are affected by complete achromatopsia, meaning they see the world in shades of gray. Studying how achromatopsia appears in different communities helps scientists understand genetic diversity and how various environmental factors can influence health outcomes.\nContext recap: Achromatopsia is a rare visual condition that affects approximately 1 in every 30,000 individuals worldwide. This means that for every 30,000 people, one person may experience this condition, which can significantly impact their ability to see colors. Among those who have achromatopsia, complete achromatopsia, where individuals cannot perceive any colors at all, is more commonly seen than incomplete achromatopsia, where some color vision may still be present. A fascinating aspect of this condition is its higher prevalence among the Pingelapese islanders, a group of people living on one of the Eastern Caroline Islands in Micronesia.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by achromatopsia ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Achromatopsia is a rare visual condition that affects approximately 1 in every 30,000 individuals worldwide. This means that for every 30,000 people, one person may experience this condition, which can significantly impact their ability to see colors. Among those who have achromatopsia, complete achromatopsia, where individuals cannot perceive any colors at all, is more commonly seen than incomplete achromatopsia, where some color vision may still be present. A fascinating aspect of this condition is its higher prevalence among the Pingelapese islanders, a group of people living on one of the Eastern Caroline Islands in Micronesia.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by achromatopsia ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Achromatopsia is a rare visual condition that affects approximately 1 in every 30,000 individuals worldwide. This means that for every 30,000 people, one person may experience this condition, which can significantly impact their ability to see colors. Among those who have achromatopsia, complete achromatopsia, where individuals cannot perceive any colors at all, is more commonly seen than incomplete achromatopsia, where some color vision may still be present. A fascinating aspect of this condition is its higher prevalence among the Pingelapese islanders, a group of people living on one of the Eastern Caroline Islands in Micronesia.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by achromatopsia ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
