          "id": "medquad-chunk-90a75dfc8a09f45e",
          "title": "How many people are affected by activated PI3K-delta syndrome ?",
          "content": "The exact number of people affected by activated PI3K-delta syndrome is not known. This condition is considered rare, and more research is needed to determine how many individuals are impacted by it. Understanding the prevalence of this syndrome can help researchers and healthcare providers better support those who have it.\nContext recap: The exact number of people affected by activated PI3K-delta syndrome is not known. This condition is considered rare, and more research is needed to determine how many individuals are impacted by it. Understanding the prevalence of this syndrome can help researchers and healthcare providers better support those who have it.\nContext recap: The exact number of people affected by activated PI3K-delta syndrome is not known. This condition is considered rare, and more research is needed to determine how many individuals are impacted by it. Understanding the prevalence of this syndrome can help researchers and healthcare providers better support those who have it. Context recap: The exact number of people affected by activated PI3K-delta syndrome is not known.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by activated PI3K-delta syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: The exact number of people affected by activated PI3K-delta syndrome is not known. This condition is considered rare, and more research is needed to determine how many individuals are impacted by it. Understanding the prevalence of this syndrome can help researchers and healthcare providers better support those who have it. Context recap: The exact number of people affected by activated PI3K-delta syndrome is not known.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by activated PI3K-delta syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
          "kind": "concept"
