          "id": "medquad-chunk-1f97d7d9acdf02b7",
          "title": "Is activated PI3K-delta syndrome inherited ?",
          "content": "Activated PI3K-delta syndrome is inherited in a way known as autosomal dominant inheritance. This means that only one copy of the altered gene from either parent is enough to cause the condition. If a parent has this genetic change, there is a chance that they can pass it on to their child. This pattern of inheritance is important to understand because it helps families know the likelihood of the condition appearing in future generations.\nContext recap: Activated PI3K-delta syndrome is inherited in a way known as autosomal dominant inheritance. This means that only one copy of the altered gene from either parent is enough to cause the condition. If a parent has this genetic change, there is a chance that they can pass it on to their child. This pattern of inheritance is important to understand because it helps families know the likelihood of the condition appearing in future generations.\nContext recap: Activated PI3K-delta syndrome is inherited in a way known as autosomal dominant inheritance. This means that only one copy of the altered gene from either parent is enough to cause the condition. If a parent has this genetic change, there is a chance that they can pass it on to their child. This pattern of inheritance is important to understand because it helps families know the likelihood of the condition appearing in future generations.\nWhy this matters: Is activated PI3K-delta syndrome inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: Activated PI3K-delta syndrome is inherited in a way known as autosomal dominant inheritance. This means that only one copy of the altered gene from either parent is enough to cause the condition. If a parent has this genetic change, there is a chance that they can pass it on to their child. This pattern of inheritance is important to understand because it helps families know the likelihood of the condition appearing in future generations.\nWhy this matters: Is activated PI3K-delta syndrome inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
