          "id": "medquad-chunk-e07eaca9ec5e7aa1",
          "title": "Is ADCY5-related dyskinesia inherited ?",
          "content": "ADCY5-related dyskinesia is a condition that is passed down through families in a way known as autosomal dominant inheritance. This means that if a child receives just one altered copy of the gene from either their mother or father, they can develop the disorder. In some cases, a person with ADCY5-related dyskinesia may inherit this gene mutation from a parent who also has the condition. However, it's also possible for the mutation to occur spontaneously, which means it can appear in a person who does not have any family history of the disorder. This situation illustrates the complexity of how genetic traits are inherited and emphasizes the importance of genetic counseling. Genetic counseling can help families understand their risks and options, providing support and information about the condition and its inheritance patterns. Understanding these concepts is crucial for affected families as they navigate the challenges associated with genetic disorders, and it can empower them to make informed decisions regarding their health and family planning.\nContext recap: ADCY5-related dyskinesia is a condition that is passed down through families in a way known as autosomal dominant inheritance. This means that if a child receives just one altered copy of the gene from either their mother or father, they can develop the disorder. In some cases, a person with ADCY5-related dyskinesia may inherit this gene mutation from a parent who also has the condition. However, it's also possible for the mutation to occur spontaneously, which means it can appear in a person who does not have any family history of the disorder.\nContext recap: ADCY5-related dyskinesia is a condition that is passed down through families in a way known as autosomal dominant inheritance. This means that if a child receives just one altered copy of the gene from either their mother or father, they can develop the disorder. In some cases, a person with ADCY5-related dyskinesia may inherit this gene mutation from a parent who also has the condition. However, it's also possible for the mutation to occur spontaneously, which means it can appear in a person who does not have any family history of the disorder.\nWhy this matters: Is ADCY5-related dyskinesia inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: ADCY5-related dyskinesia is a condition that is passed down through families in a way known as autosomal dominant inheritance. This means that if a child receives just one altered copy of the gene from either their mother or father, they can develop the disorder. In some cases, a person with ADCY5-related dyskinesia may inherit this gene mutation from a parent who also has the condition. However, it's also possible for the mutation to occur spontaneously, which means it can appear in a person who does not have any family history of the disorder.\nWhy this matters: Is ADCY5-related dyskinesia inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
