          "id": "medquad-chunk-9741d024537a6ebe",
          "title": "How many people are affected by adenosine monophosphate deaminase deficiency ?",
          "content": "Adenosine monophosphate (AMP) deaminase deficiency is an important inherited muscle disorder that affects how our muscles function. It is particularly common in white populations, where it is estimated that about 1 in every 50 to 100 individuals may be affected by this condition. This means that if you were to gather a group of 100 people, it is likely that one or two of them could have this disorder. However, the situation is different for other ethnic groups. For example, in African American populations, the prevalence drops significantly, with only about 1 in 40,000 individuals affected. This indicates that the condition is much rarer in this group. Furthermore, in the Japanese population, the occurrence of AMP deaminase deficiency is even less common, suggesting that genetic factors play a crucial role in how this disorder is distributed among different ethnicities. Understanding these differences is important for medical professionals as they work to provide the best care for individuals with this condition.\nContext recap: Adenosine monophosphate (AMP) deaminase deficiency is an important inherited muscle disorder that affects how our muscles function. It is particularly common in white populations, where it is estimated that about 1 in every 50 to 100 individuals may be affected by this condition. This means that if you were to gather a group of 100 people, it is likely that one or two of them could have this disorder. However, the situation is different for other ethnic groups.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by adenosine monophosphate deaminase deficiency ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Adenosine monophosphate (AMP) deaminase deficiency is an important inherited muscle disorder that affects how our muscles function. It is particularly common in white populations, where it is estimated that about 1 in every 50 to 100 individuals may be affected by this condition. This means that if you were to gather a group of 100 people, it is likely that one or two of them could have this disorder. However, the situation is different for other ethnic groups.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by adenosine monophosphate deaminase deficiency ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Adenosine monophosphate (AMP) deaminase deficiency is an important inherited muscle disorder that affects how our muscles function. It is particularly common in white populations, where it is estimated that about 1 in every 50 to 100 individuals may be affected by this condition. This means that if you were to gather a group of 100 people, it is likely that one or two of them could have this disorder. However, the situation is different for other ethnic groups.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by adenosine monophosphate deaminase deficiency ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
          "kind": "concept"
