          "id": "medquad-chunk-04a2715cf0d34b48",
          "title": "How many people are affected by Aicardi syndrome ?",
          "content": "Aicardi syndrome is considered an extremely rare genetic disorder that affects newborns. In the United States, it occurs in about 1 out of every 105,000 to 167,000 babies. This means that for every 105,000 to 167,000 newborns, only one will be diagnosed with this condition. Given its rarity, researchers estimate that there are approximately 4,000 individuals living with Aicardi syndrome around the globe. Because so few people are affected by this disorder, it is very important for both the public and medical professionals to be aware of it. Understanding Aicardi syndrome can help provide better support for those who are diagnosed and their families, ensuring they receive the care and resources they need.\nContext recap: Aicardi syndrome is considered an extremely rare genetic disorder that affects newborns. In the United States, it occurs in about 1 out of every 105,000 to 167,000 babies. This means that for every 105,000 to 167,000 newborns, only one will be diagnosed with this condition. Given its rarity, researchers estimate that there are approximately 4,000 individuals living with Aicardi syndrome around the globe.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by Aicardi syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Aicardi syndrome is considered an extremely rare genetic disorder that affects newborns. In the United States, it occurs in about 1 out of every 105,000 to 167,000 babies. This means that for every 105,000 to 167,000 newborns, only one will be diagnosed with this condition. Given its rarity, researchers estimate that there are approximately 4,000 individuals living with Aicardi syndrome around the globe.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by Aicardi syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: Aicardi syndrome is considered an extremely rare genetic disorder that affects newborns. In the United States, it occurs in about 1 out of every 105,000 to 167,000 babies. This means that for every 105,000 to 167,000 newborns, only one will be diagnosed with this condition. Given its rarity, researchers estimate that there are approximately 4,000 individuals living with Aicardi syndrome around the globe.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by Aicardi syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
