          "id": "medquad-chunk-154e98b845c68e74",
          "title": "How many people are affected by Alexander disease ?",
          "content": "The exact number of individuals affected by Alexander disease remains uncertain. Since the disorder was first recognized in 1949, approximately 500 cases have been documented in medical literature. This indicates that Alexander disease is relatively rare. However, it is important to note that the actual number of cases could be higher, as many individuals may not receive a diagnosis or may go unreported. This highlights the need for increased awareness and research into the condition to better understand its true prevalence in the population.\nContext recap: The exact number of individuals affected by Alexander disease remains uncertain. Since the disorder was first recognized in 1949, approximately 500 cases have been documented in medical literature. This indicates that Alexander disease is relatively rare. However, it is important to note that the actual number of cases could be higher, as many individuals may not receive a diagnosis or may go unreported.\nContext recap: The exact number of individuals affected by Alexander disease remains uncertain. Since the disorder was first recognized in 1949, approximately 500 cases have been documented in medical literature. This indicates that Alexander disease is relatively rare. However, it is important to note that the actual number of cases could be higher, as many individuals may not receive a diagnosis or may go unreported.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by Alexander disease ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: The exact number of individuals affected by Alexander disease remains uncertain. Since the disorder was first recognized in 1949, approximately 500 cases have been documented in medical literature. This indicates that Alexander disease is relatively rare. However, it is important to note that the actual number of cases could be higher, as many individuals may not receive a diagnosis or may go unreported.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by Alexander disease ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
