          "title": "How many people are affected by Alpers-Huttenlocher syndrome ?",
          "content": "Alpers-Huttenlocher syndrome is a rare condition, affecting approximately 1 in every 100,000 individuals. This means that while it is not very common, it does occur in the population, and awareness of the syndrome is important for early diagnosis and management.\nContext recap: Alpers-Huttenlocher syndrome is a rare condition, affecting approximately 1 in every 100,000 individuals. This means that while it is not very common, it does occur in the population, and awareness of the syndrome is important for early diagnosis and management.\nContext recap: Alpers-Huttenlocher syndrome is a rare condition, affecting approximately 1 in every 100,000 individuals. This means that while it is not very common, it does occur in the population, and awareness of the syndrome is important for early diagnosis and management. Context recap: Alpers-Huttenlocher syndrome is a rare condition, affecting approximately 1 in every 100,000 individuals. This means that while it is not very common, it does occur in the population, and awareness of the syndrome is important for early diagnosis and management.\nContext recap: Alpers-Huttenlocher syndrome is a rare condition, affecting approximately 1 in every 100,000 individuals. This means that while it is not very common, it does occur in the population, and awareness of the syndrome is important for early diagnosis and management. Context recap: Alpers-Huttenlocher syndrome is a rare condition, affecting approximately 1 in every 100,000 individuals. This means that while it is not very common, it does occur in the population, and awareness of the syndrome is important for early diagnosis and management.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by Alpers-Huttenlocher syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
