          "id": "medquad-chunk-c170b8739302278a",
          "title": "Is alpha thalassemia X-linked intellectual disability syndrome inherited ?",
          "content": "Alpha thalassemia X-linked intellectual disability syndrome is inherited through a pattern known as X-linked recessive inheritance. This means that the gene responsible for the condition, called the ATRX gene, is found on the X chromosome, which is one of the two types of sex chromosomes that determine an individual's sex. Males have one X chromosome and one Y chromosome, while females have two X chromosomes. Because males only have one X chromosome, if they inherit a mutated version of the ATRX gene, they will develop the condition. This is because there is no second X chromosome to provide a healthy copy of the gene that could potentially compensate for the mutation.\nOn the other hand, females have two X chromosomes. If a female inherits one mutated ATRX gene, she usually has a second, healthy copy of the gene on her other X chromosome. This healthy copy can often make up for the mutated one, which is why females who carry one mutated ATRX gene typically do not show any symptoms of alpha thalassemia X-linked intellectual disability syndrome.\nAn important aspect of X-linked inheritance is that fathers cannot pass X-linked traits to their sons. This is because sons inherit their Y chromosome from their fathers and their X chromosome from their mothers. Understanding this pattern of inheritance is crucial for families as it helps them comprehend how the condition may be passed down through generations and the likelihood of its occurrence in future offspring.\nContext recap: Alpha thalassemia X-linked intellectual disability syndrome is inherited through a pattern known as X-linked recessive inheritance. This means that the gene responsible for the condition, called the ATRX gene, is found on the X chromosome, which is one of the two types of sex chromosomes that determine an individual's sex. Males have one X chromosome and one Y chromosome, while females have two X chromosomes. Because males only have one X chromosome, if they inherit a mutated version of the ATRX gene, they will develop the condition.\nWhy this matters: Is alpha thalassemia X-linked intellectual disability syndrome inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Alpha thalassemia X-linked intellectual disability syndrome is inherited through a pattern known as X-linked recessive inheritance. This means that the gene responsible for the condition, called the ATRX gene, is found on the X chromosome, which is one of the two types of sex chromosomes that determine an individual's sex. Males have one X chromosome and one Y chromosome, while females have two X chromosomes. Because males only have one X chromosome, if they inherit a mutated version of the ATRX gene, they will develop the condition.\nWhy this matters: Is alpha thalassemia X-linked intellectual disability syndrome inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: Alpha thalassemia X-linked intellectual disability syndrome is inherited through a pattern known as X-linked recessive inheritance. This means that the gene responsible for the condition, called the ATRX gene, is found on the X chromosome, which is one of the two types of sex chromosomes that determine an individual's sex. Males have one X chromosome and one Y chromosome, while females have two X chromosomes. Because males only have one X chromosome, if they inherit a mutated version of the ATRX gene, they will develop the condition.\nWhy this matters: Is alpha thalassemia X-linked intellectual disability syndrome inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
