          "content": "Alpha-mannosidosis is a very rare condition, affecting about 1 in every 500,000 people around the world. This means that it is not commonly seen, but it is important for medical professionals to be aware of it.\nContext recap: Alpha-mannosidosis is a very rare condition, affecting about 1 in every 500,000 people around the world. This means that it is not commonly seen, but it is important for medical professionals to be aware of it.\nContext recap: Alpha-mannosidosis is a very rare condition, affecting about 1 in every 500,000 people around the world. This means that it is not commonly seen, but it is important for medical professionals to be aware of it. Context recap: Alpha-mannosidosis is a very rare condition, affecting about 1 in every 500,000 people around the world. This means that it is not commonly seen, but it is important for medical professionals to be aware of it.\nContext recap: Alpha-mannosidosis is a very rare condition, affecting about 1 in every 500,000 people around the world. This means that it is not commonly seen, but it is important for medical professionals to be aware of it. Context recap: Alpha-mannosidosis is a very rare condition, affecting about 1 in every 500,000 people around the world. This means that it is not commonly seen, but it is important for medical professionals to be aware of it.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by alpha-mannosidosis ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
