          "id": "medquad-chunk-5e456ba6ee445137",
          "title": "What is (are) alpha-methylacyl-CoA racemase deficiency ?",
          "content": "Alpha-methylacyl-CoA racemase (AMACR) deficiency is a rare genetic disorder that primarily affects the nervous system, leading to a range of neurological challenges that typically manifest in adulthood. This condition is characterized by a gradual decline in cognitive abilities, which means that individuals may find it increasingly difficult to think clearly or remember things as time goes on. In addition to cognitive decline, people with AMACR deficiency may experience seizures, which are sudden bursts of electrical activity in the brain that can cause convulsions or loss of consciousness, as well as migraines, which are intense headaches often accompanied by nausea and sensitivity to light.\nOne of the more severe aspects of AMACR deficiency is the occurrence of acute episodes of brain dysfunction, known as encephalopathy. During these episodes, individuals may experience symptoms similar to those of a stroke, such as confusion, altered consciousness, and even physical damage to the brain, which can lead to lasting effects.\nMoreover, individuals with this condition may suffer from sensorimotor neuropathy, which is a type of nerve damage that can result in weakness and a loss of sensation in the arms and legs. This can make it difficult for them to perform everyday tasks. Muscle stiffness, known as spasticity, is another common symptom, making movement challenging and uncomfortable. Coordination issues, referred to as ataxia, can also arise, causing difficulties in balance and fine motor skills.\nLastly, vision problems may develop due to damage to the retina, the light-sensitive layer at the back of the eye. This can lead to difficulties in seeing clearly, which can further impact the quality of life for those affected by AMACR deficiency. Overall, AMACR deficiency is a complex disorder that requires careful management and support for those living with it.\nContext recap: Alpha-methylacyl-CoA racemase (AMACR) deficiency is a rare genetic disorder that primarily affects the nervous system, leading to a range of neurological challenges that typically manifest in adulthood. This condition is characterized by a gradual decline in cognitive abilities, which means that individuals may find it increasingly difficult to think clearly or remember things as time goes on. In addition to cognitive decline, people with AMACR deficiency may experience seizures, which are sudden bursts of electrical activity in the brain that can cause convulsions or loss of consciousness, as well as migraines, which are intense headaches often accompanied by nausea and sensitivity to light. One of the more severe aspects of AMACR deficiency is the occurrence of acute episodes of brain dysfunction, known as encephalopathy.\nContext recap: Alpha-methylacyl-CoA racemase (AMACR) deficiency is a rare genetic disorder that primarily affects the nervous system, leading to a range of neurological challenges that typically manifest in adulthood. This condition is characterized by a gradual decline in cognitive abilities, which means that individuals may find it increasingly difficult to think clearly or remember things as time goes on. In addition to cognitive decline, people with AMACR deficiency may experience seizures, which are sudden bursts of electrical activity in the brain that can cause convulsions or loss of consciousness, as well as migraines, which are intense headaches often accompanied by nausea and sensitivity to light. One of the more severe aspects of AMACR deficiency is the occurrence of acute episodes of brain dysfunction, known as encephalopathy.",
          "kind": "concept"
