          "id": "medquad-chunk-2f8f195acc3b1141",
          "title": "How many people are affected by alpha-methylacyl-CoA racemase deficiency ?",
          "content": "Alpha-methylacyl-CoA racemase (AMACR) deficiency is classified as a rare genetic disorder. The precise number of individuals affected by this condition is not clearly established, making it difficult to determine how many people are impacted overall. However, medical literature has recorded at least 10 distinct cases of AMACR deficiency. This suggests that while the disorder is uncommon, it is a real condition that can affect certain individuals, highlighting the importance of awareness and research in understanding rare genetic disorders.\nContext recap: Alpha-methylacyl-CoA racemase (AMACR) deficiency is classified as a rare genetic disorder. The precise number of individuals affected by this condition is not clearly established, making it difficult to determine how many people are impacted overall. However, medical literature has recorded at least 10 distinct cases of AMACR deficiency. This suggests that while the disorder is uncommon, it is a real condition that can affect certain individuals, highlighting the importance of awareness and research in understanding rare genetic disorders.\nContext recap: Alpha-methylacyl-CoA racemase (AMACR) deficiency is classified as a rare genetic disorder. The precise number of individuals affected by this condition is not clearly established, making it difficult to determine how many people are impacted overall. However, medical literature has recorded at least 10 distinct cases of AMACR deficiency. This suggests that while the disorder is uncommon, it is a real condition that can affect certain individuals, highlighting the importance of awareness and research in understanding rare genetic disorders.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by alpha-methylacyl-CoA racemase deficiency ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Alpha-methylacyl-CoA racemase (AMACR) deficiency is classified as a rare genetic disorder. The precise number of individuals affected by this condition is not clearly established, making it difficult to determine how many people are impacted overall. However, medical literature has recorded at least 10 distinct cases of AMACR deficiency. This suggests that while the disorder is uncommon, it is a real condition that can affect certain individuals, highlighting the importance of awareness and research in understanding rare genetic disorders.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by alpha-methylacyl-CoA racemase deficiency ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
