          "title": "How many people are affected by Alport syndrome ?",
          "content": "Alport syndrome is a genetic condition that affects approximately 1 in every 50,000 newborns. This means that while it is not very common, it is significant enough to be recognized in the medical community.\nContext recap: Alport syndrome is a genetic condition that affects approximately 1 in every 50,000 newborns. This means that while it is not very common, it is significant enough to be recognized in the medical community.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by Alport syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Alport syndrome is a genetic condition that affects approximately 1 in every 50,000 newborns. This means that while it is not very common, it is significant enough to be recognized in the medical community. Context recap: Alport syndrome is a genetic condition that affects approximately 1 in every 50,000 newborns. This means that while it is not very common, it is significant enough to be recognized in the medical community.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by Alport syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Alport syndrome is a genetic condition that affects approximately 1 in every 50,000 newborns. This means that while it is not very common, it is significant enough to be recognized in the medical community. Context recap: Alport syndrome is a genetic condition that affects approximately 1 in every 50,000 newborns. This means that while it is not very common, it is significant enough to be recognized in the medical community.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by Alport syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
