          "id": "medquad-chunk-e9b087325fb7fcc0",
          "title": "How many people are affected by alternating hemiplegia of childhood ?",
          "content": "Alternating hemiplegia of childhood is classified as a rare neurological condition that impacts around 1 in every 1 million individuals. This strikingly low prevalence underscores the distinctiveness of this disorder. It is crucial for both the public and medical community to raise awareness about this condition. Increased understanding can lead to better support and resources for those who are affected, as well as encourage further research aimed at uncovering more about its causes and potential treatments.\nContext recap: Alternating hemiplegia of childhood is classified as a rare neurological condition that impacts around 1 in every 1 million individuals. This strikingly low prevalence underscores the distinctiveness of this disorder. It is crucial for both the public and medical community to raise awareness about this condition. Increased understanding can lead to better support and resources for those who are affected, as well as encourage further research aimed at uncovering more about its causes and potential treatments.\nContext recap: Alternating hemiplegia of childhood is classified as a rare neurological condition that impacts around 1 in every 1 million individuals. This strikingly low prevalence underscores the distinctiveness of this disorder. It is crucial for both the public and medical community to raise awareness about this condition. Increased understanding can lead to better support and resources for those who are affected, as well as encourage further research aimed at uncovering more about its causes and potential treatments.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by alternating hemiplegia of childhood ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Alternating hemiplegia of childhood is classified as a rare neurological condition that impacts around 1 in every 1 million individuals. This strikingly low prevalence underscores the distinctiveness of this disorder. It is crucial for both the public and medical community to raise awareness about this condition. Increased understanding can lead to better support and resources for those who are affected, as well as encourage further research aimed at uncovering more about its causes and potential treatments.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by alternating hemiplegia of childhood ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
