          "id": "medquad-chunk-5810cde652822416",
          "title": "How many people are affected by amyotrophic lateral sclerosis ?",
          "content": "Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) is a serious neurological condition that impacts the lives of many individuals. In the United States, around 5,000 people are diagnosed with ALS each year, highlighting the importance of awareness and research surrounding this disorder. When we look at the global perspective, ALS affects approximately 2 to 5 individuals out of every 100,000 people. This statistic shows that while ALS is relatively rare, it still poses a significant challenge for those who are diagnosed. Interestingly, only a small fraction of ALS cases can be traced back to a known genetic cause, which means that for many, the reasons behind the onset of the disease remain unclear. Furthermore, there are specific populations where ALS appears to be more prevalent. For example, among the Chamorro people of Guam and those from the Kii Peninsula in Japan, a variant of ALS known as ALS-PDC is reported to occur at a staggering rate—up to 100 times more frequently than in other populations. This unique occurrence raises important questions about environmental and genetic factors that may contribute to the disease. However, it is important to note that ALS-PDC has not been documented outside of these specific groups. By understanding the prevalence and variations of ALS, researchers and healthcare providers can work towards developing better support systems and treatment options for those affected by this challenging condition.\nContext recap: Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) is a serious neurological condition that impacts the lives of many individuals. In the United States, around 5,000 people are diagnosed with ALS each year, highlighting the importance of awareness and research surrounding this disorder. When we look at the global perspective, ALS affects approximately 2 to 5 individuals out of every 100,000 people. This statistic shows that while ALS is relatively rare, it still poses a significant challenge for those who are diagnosed.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by amyotrophic lateral sclerosis ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) is a serious neurological condition that impacts the lives of many individuals. In the United States, around 5,000 people are diagnosed with ALS each year, highlighting the importance of awareness and research surrounding this disorder. When we look at the global perspective, ALS affects approximately 2 to 5 individuals out of every 100,000 people. This statistic shows that while ALS is relatively rare, it still poses a significant challenge for those who are diagnosed.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by amyotrophic lateral sclerosis ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) is a serious neurological condition that impacts the lives of many individuals. In the United States, around 5,000 people are diagnosed with ALS each year, highlighting the importance of awareness and research surrounding this disorder. When we look at the global perspective, ALS affects approximately 2 to 5 individuals out of every 100,000 people. This statistic shows that while ALS is relatively rare, it still poses a significant challenge for those who are diagnosed.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by amyotrophic lateral sclerosis ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
