          "id": "medquad-chunk-4f6ed18cb5e185d7",
          "title": "How many people are affected by androgen insensitivity syndrome ?",
          "content": "Androgen insensitivity syndrome (AIS) is a medical condition that affects a relatively small number of individuals. Specifically, complete androgen insensitivity syndrome is estimated to occur in approximately 2 to 5 out of every 100,000 people who are genetically male. This means that while it is not very common, it is important to recognize its existence. Additionally, partial androgen insensitivity syndrome is thought to be at least as prevalent as the complete form, indicating that many individuals may experience varying degrees of this condition. On the other hand, mild androgen insensitivity syndrome is much rarer. Understanding how many people are affected by these conditions is crucial, as it can help raise awareness and encourage research efforts aimed at improving our understanding and treatment of androgen insensitivity syndrome. By learning more about these conditions, we can better support those who are affected and work towards finding effective solutions for their health and well-being.\nContext recap: Androgen insensitivity syndrome (AIS) is a medical condition that affects a relatively small number of individuals. Specifically, complete androgen insensitivity syndrome is estimated to occur in approximately 2 to 5 out of every 100,000 people who are genetically male. This means that while it is not very common, it is important to recognize its existence. Additionally, partial androgen insensitivity syndrome is thought to be at least as prevalent as the complete form, indicating that many individuals may experience varying degrees of this condition.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by androgen insensitivity syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Androgen insensitivity syndrome (AIS) is a medical condition that affects a relatively small number of individuals. Specifically, complete androgen insensitivity syndrome is estimated to occur in approximately 2 to 5 out of every 100,000 people who are genetically male. This means that while it is not very common, it is important to recognize its existence. Additionally, partial androgen insensitivity syndrome is thought to be at least as prevalent as the complete form, indicating that many individuals may experience varying degrees of this condition.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by androgen insensitivity syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Androgen insensitivity syndrome (AIS) is a medical condition that affects a relatively small number of individuals. Specifically, complete androgen insensitivity syndrome is estimated to occur in approximately 2 to 5 out of every 100,000 people who are genetically male. This means that while it is not very common, it is important to recognize its existence. Additionally, partial androgen insensitivity syndrome is thought to be at least as prevalent as the complete form, indicating that many individuals may experience varying degrees of this condition.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by androgen insensitivity syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
