          "id": "medquad-chunk-a1e085c2a7daaaa2",
          "title": "Is androgen insensitivity syndrome inherited ?",
          "content": "Androgen insensitivity syndrome is a genetic condition that is passed down through a specific inheritance pattern known as X-linked recessive inheritance. To understand this, we need to look at chromosomes, which are structures in our cells that carry our genes. Humans have two types of sex chromosomes: X and Y. Females typically have two X chromosomes (XX), while males have one X and one Y chromosome (XY). In this condition, the gene that is altered and causes the syndrome is located on the X chromosome.\nFor individuals who are genetically male, having just one altered copy of this gene on their single X chromosome is enough to lead to the development of androgen insensitivity syndrome. This is because males do not have a second X chromosome that could potentially compensate for the mutation. On the other hand, for genetically female individuals, both copies of the gene must be mutated for them to develop the condition. This difference in how the condition affects males and females is why we see that males are affected by X-linked recessive disorders much more frequently than females.\nResearch indicates that about two-thirds of all cases of androgen insensitivity syndrome are inherited from mothers who carry a mutated version of the AR gene on one of their X chromosomes. These mothers may not show any symptoms of the syndrome themselves because they have a second, normal copy of the gene that can function properly. However, they can pass the mutated gene to their children.\nThe remaining cases of androgen insensitivity syndrome occur due to new mutations. These mutations can happen in the mother’s egg cell before conception or during the early stages of fetal development. This means that even if there is no family history of the condition, it can still appear in a child due to these spontaneous genetic changes. Understanding the inheritance patterns of genetic conditions like androgen insensitivity syndrome helps us learn more about how traits and disorders are passed from one generation to the next, and it emphasizes the importance of genetics in our health and development.\nContext recap: Androgen insensitivity syndrome is a genetic condition that is passed down through a specific inheritance pattern known as X-linked recessive inheritance. To understand this, we need to look at chromosomes, which are structures in our cells that carry our genes. Humans have two types of sex chromosomes: X and Y. Females typically have two X chromosomes (XX), while males have one X and one Y chromosome (XY).\nWhy this matters: Is androgen insensitivity syndrome inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: Androgen insensitivity syndrome is a genetic condition that is passed down through a specific inheritance pattern known as X-linked recessive inheritance. To understand this, we need to look at chromosomes, which are structures in our cells that carry our genes. Humans have two types of sex chromosomes: X and Y. Females typically have two X chromosomes (XX), while males have one X and one Y chromosome (XY).\nWhy this matters: Is androgen insensitivity syndrome inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
