          "id": "medquad-chunk-8e39e60c827007bc",
          "title": "What is (are) antiphospholipid syndrome ?",
          "content": "Antiphospholipid syndrome is a medical condition that causes the body to have an increased tendency to form unusual blood clots, known as thromboses. This condition is part of a broader category called thrombophilia, which refers to the tendency to develop these clots more easily than normal. In people with antiphospholipid syndrome, these clots can form in almost any blood vessel in the body, but they are most commonly found in the blood vessels of the legs. When a clot forms in the brain, it can block blood flow, which can lead to a stroke, a serious medical emergency that requires immediate attention.\nAntiphospholipid syndrome is classified as an autoimmune disorder. Autoimmune disorders occur when the immune system, which is supposed to protect the body from infections and diseases, mistakenly attacks the body's own tissues and organs. This can lead to a variety of health issues. Women who are diagnosed with antiphospholipid syndrome face a higher risk of complications during pregnancy. These complications can include high blood pressure caused by pregnancy, known as preeclampsia, problems with the placenta, which is essential for nourishing the baby (this condition is called placental insufficiency), premature birth, or even loss of the pregnancy, which is referred to as miscarriage. Additionally, women with this syndrome are more likely to experience blood clots during pregnancy compared to other times in their lives. Babies born to mothers with antiphospholipid syndrome may be smaller than average and underweight, which can lead to further health concerns.\nOften, the first signs of antiphospholipid syndrome are related to blood clots or complications during pregnancy. While this condition typically appears in early to mid-adulthood, it can start at any age, affecting individuals differently. Other symptoms that may occur include a lower number of blood clotting cells called platelets, a condition known as thrombocytopenia. This can lead to increased bleeding or bruising. There may also be a lack of red blood cells, known as anemia, which occurs due to their early breakdown, a process called hemolysis. Additionally, some individuals may notice a purplish discoloration of the skin, known as livedo reticularis, which is caused by issues in the tiny blood vessels of the skin.\nIndividuals with antiphospholipid syndrome may also experience skin sores, known as ulcers, migraine headaches, heart problems, or learning difficulties. It is important to note that many people with this syndrome also have other autoimmune disorders, such as systemic lupus erythematosus, which can complicate their health further.\nIn rare cases, some individuals with antiphospholipid syndrome develop blood clots in multiple blood vessels throughout their body. This can block blood flow to important organs, leading to organ failure, which is a serious and life-threatening condition. This severe form is known as catastrophic antiphospholipid syndrome (CAPS). CAPS can affect vital organs such as the kidneys, lungs, brain, heart, and liver, and it is fatal in more than half of those affected. Fortunately, less than one percent of individuals with antiphospholipid syndrome develop CAPS, but it is crucial for those diagnosed with the syndrome to be aware of the potential risks and complications associated with their condition. Regular medical check-ups and monitoring can help manage the symptoms and reduce the risk of serious complications.\nContext recap: Antiphospholipid syndrome is a medical condition that causes the body to have an increased tendency to form unusual blood clots, known as thromboses. This condition is part of a broader category called thrombophilia, which refers to the tendency to develop these clots more easily than normal. In people with antiphospholipid syndrome, these clots can form in almost any blood vessel in the body, but they are most commonly found in the blood vessels of the legs. When a clot forms in the brain, it can block blood flow, which can lead to a stroke, a serious medical emergency that requires immediate attention.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) antiphospholipid syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Antiphospholipid syndrome is a medical condition that causes the body to have an increased tendency to form unusual blood clots, known as thromboses. This condition is part of a broader category called thrombophilia, which refers to the tendency to develop these clots more easily than normal. In people with antiphospholipid syndrome, these clots can form in almost any blood vessel in the body, but they are most commonly found in the blood vessels of the legs. When a clot forms in the brain, it can block blood flow, which can lead to a stroke, a serious medical emergency that requires immediate attention.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) antiphospholipid syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
          "kind": "concept"
