          "id": "medquad-chunk-787357d92c950491",
          "title": "How many people are affected by arginase deficiency ?",
          "content": "Arginase deficiency is a very rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to break down certain proteins. It is estimated that this condition occurs in about 1 in every 300,000 to 1,000,000 individuals. This means that only a small number of people are impacted by this disorder, highlighting its rarity in the general population. Understanding such rare conditions is important in the field of medical genetics, as it helps researchers and healthcare professionals to better support those who are affected and to develop potential treatments.\nContext recap: Arginase deficiency is a very rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to break down certain proteins. It is estimated that this condition occurs in about 1 in every 300,000 to 1,000,000 individuals. This means that only a small number of people are impacted by this disorder, highlighting its rarity in the general population. Understanding such rare conditions is important in the field of medical genetics, as it helps researchers and healthcare professionals to better support those who are affected and to develop potential treatments.\nContext recap: Arginase deficiency is a very rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to break down certain proteins. It is estimated that this condition occurs in about 1 in every 300,000 to 1,000,000 individuals. This means that only a small number of people are impacted by this disorder, highlighting its rarity in the general population. Understanding such rare conditions is important in the field of medical genetics, as it helps researchers and healthcare professionals to better support those who are affected and to develop potential treatments.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by arginase deficiency ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Arginase deficiency is a very rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to break down certain proteins. It is estimated that this condition occurs in about 1 in every 300,000 to 1,000,000 individuals. This means that only a small number of people are impacted by this disorder, highlighting its rarity in the general population. Understanding such rare conditions is important in the field of medical genetics, as it helps researchers and healthcare professionals to better support those who are affected and to develop potential treatments.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by arginase deficiency ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
          "kind": "concept"
