          "id": "medquad-chunk-428906497cf1a522",
          "title": "Is argininosuccinic aciduria inherited ?",
          "content": "Argininosuccinic aciduria is a genetic condition that is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner. This means that for a person to be affected by this condition, both copies of the gene in their cells must have mutations. In simpler terms, each person has two copies of most genes, one inherited from their mother and one from their father. In the case of argininosuccinic aciduria, if both of these copies are faulty, the individual will experience the symptoms of the condition. Interestingly, the parents of a child with this condition usually carry one copy of the mutated gene each. However, they often do not show any signs or symptoms of the condition themselves. This is an important concept for families to understand, as it helps them see how genetic traits can be passed down from parents to children over generations. By learning about this inheritance pattern, families can make informed decisions regarding health and genetic counseling, which can be very beneficial for future generations.\nContext recap: Argininosuccinic aciduria is a genetic condition that is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner. This means that for a person to be affected by this condition, both copies of the gene in their cells must have mutations. In simpler terms, each person has two copies of most genes, one inherited from their mother and one from their father. In the case of argininosuccinic aciduria, if both of these copies are faulty, the individual will experience the symptoms of the condition.\nContext recap: Argininosuccinic aciduria is a genetic condition that is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner. This means that for a person to be affected by this condition, both copies of the gene in their cells must have mutations. In simpler terms, each person has two copies of most genes, one inherited from their mother and one from their father. In the case of argininosuccinic aciduria, if both of these copies are faulty, the individual will experience the symptoms of the condition.\nWhy this matters: Is argininosuccinic aciduria inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
