          "title": "How many people are affected by aromatic l-amino acid decarboxylase deficiency ?",
          "content": "Aromatic l-amino acid decarboxylase (AADC) deficiency is considered a very rare genetic disorder. To date, medical literature has documented only about 100 individuals who have been diagnosed with this condition across the globe. Notably, around 20 percent of these documented cases originate from Taiwan. The extreme rarity of AADC deficiency makes it a fascinating subject for researchers in the field of medical genetics. This condition emphasizes the need for continuous research efforts to deepen our understanding of its underlying causes, the symptoms that individuals may experience, and the potential treatments that could improve their quality of life.\nContext recap: Aromatic l-amino acid decarboxylase (AADC) deficiency is considered a very rare genetic disorder. To date, medical literature has documented only about 100 individuals who have been diagnosed with this condition across the globe. Notably, around 20 percent of these documented cases originate from Taiwan. The extreme rarity of AADC deficiency makes it a fascinating subject for researchers in the field of medical genetics.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by aromatic l-amino acid decarboxylase deficiency ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Aromatic l-amino acid decarboxylase (AADC) deficiency is considered a very rare genetic disorder. To date, medical literature has documented only about 100 individuals who have been diagnosed with this condition across the globe. Notably, around 20 percent of these documented cases originate from Taiwan. The extreme rarity of AADC deficiency makes it a fascinating subject for researchers in the field of medical genetics.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by aromatic l-amino acid decarboxylase deficiency ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: Aromatic l-amino acid decarboxylase (AADC) deficiency is considered a very rare genetic disorder. To date, medical literature has documented only about 100 individuals who have been diagnosed with this condition across the globe. Notably, around 20 percent of these documented cases originate from Taiwan. The extreme rarity of AADC deficiency makes it a fascinating subject for researchers in the field of medical genetics.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by aromatic l-amino acid decarboxylase deficiency ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
