          "id": "medquad-chunk-d675b889592570e8",
          "title": "What is (are) arterial tortuosity syndrome ?",
          "content": "Arterial tortuosity syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the connective tissue in the body. Connective tissue is essential because it provides support and flexibility to various structures, including blood vessels, skin, and joints. In this syndrome, the arteries, which are the blood vessels that carry oxygen-rich blood away from the heart, develop unusual twists and turns. This twisting happens because the arteries become longer than normal; since the ends of the arteries are anchored in place, the extra length causes them to curve and twist in unexpected ways.\nIn addition to the twisting of the arteries, individuals with arterial tortuosity syndrome may experience other blood vessel issues. These can include narrowing of the arteries, known as stenosis, and bulging of the arteries, called aneurysms. There may also be clusters of enlarged blood vessels just beneath the skin, which are referred to as telangiectasia.\nThe complications that arise from these abnormal blood vessels can be very serious and potentially life-threatening. For example, if an aneurysm ruptures, or if there is a tear in the wall of an artery, it can lead to significant blood loss. Moreover, if blood flow to vital organs such as the heart, lungs, or brain is obstructed, it can result in severe health problems, including heart attacks, respiratory issues, or strokes. The narrowing of the arteries (stenosis) can make the heart work harder to pump blood, which may eventually lead to heart failure. Because of these serious complications, arterial tortuosity syndrome can often be fatal in childhood. However, some individuals with milder forms of the disorder may live into adulthood.\nBeyond the circulatory system, arterial tortuosity syndrome can also cause issues related to connective tissue in other parts of the body. For instance, individuals may have joints that are either overly flexible, making them hypermobile, or they may have joints that are stiff and limited in movement, known as contractures. The skin may also be unusually soft and stretchy.\nPhysical features associated with this syndrome can include long fingers and toes, a condition known as arachnodactyly, curvature of the spine (scoliosis), or chest deformities such as a sunken chest (pectus excavatum) or a protruding chest (pectus carinatum). Additionally, some individuals may experience protrusion of organs through gaps in the muscles, known as hernias, elongation of the intestines, or the presence of pouches in the intestinal walls called diverticula.\nPeople with arterial tortuosity syndrome often have distinctive facial features that may make them appear older than their actual age. These features can include a long, narrow face with droopy cheeks, narrowed eye openings (blepharophimosis) with the outer corners pointing downward (downslanting palpebral fissures), a beaked nose with soft cartilage, a high, arched roof of the mouth (palate), a small lower jaw (micrognathia), and large ears. Furthermore, the cornea, which is the clear front covering of the eye, may be cone-shaped and abnormally thin, a condition known as keratoconus.\nOverall, arterial tortuosity syndrome is a complex condition that requires careful medical management and support. Understanding its implications can help in providing better care for those affected by this disorder.\nContext recap: Arterial tortuosity syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the connective tissue in the body. Connective tissue is essential because it provides support and flexibility to various structures, including blood vessels, skin, and joints. In this syndrome, the arteries, which are the blood vessels that carry oxygen-rich blood away from the heart, develop unusual twists and turns. This twisting happens because the arteries become longer than normal; since the ends of the arteries are anchored in place, the extra length causes them to curve and twist in unexpected ways.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) arterial tortuosity syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Arterial tortuosity syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the connective tissue in the body. Connective tissue is essential because it provides support and flexibility to various structures, including blood vessels, skin, and joints. In this syndrome, the arteries, which are the blood vessels that carry oxygen-rich blood away from the heart, develop unusual twists and turns. This twisting happens because the arteries become longer than normal; since the ends of the arteries are anchored in place, the extra length causes them to curve and twist in unexpected ways.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) arterial tortuosity syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
