          "id": "medquad-chunk-687aa3e6f1edff36",
          "title": "Is arterial tortuosity syndrome inherited ?",
          "content": "Arterial tortuosity syndrome is a genetic condition that is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner. This means that for a person to be affected by this syndrome, both copies of the gene in each of their cells must have mutations. In simpler terms, an individual needs to inherit a mutated gene from both parents to develop the condition. Typically, the parents of someone with arterial tortuosity syndrome each carry one copy of the mutated gene. However, they usually do not show any signs or symptoms of the syndrome themselves, which is why they may not even be aware that they are carriers. Understanding this pattern of inheritance is crucial for families. It allows them to assess their risk of having a child with the syndrome and consider options for genetic counseling, which can provide guidance and support for family planning and health management. This knowledge empowers families to make informed decisions about their health and the health of future generations.\nContext recap: Arterial tortuosity syndrome is a genetic condition that is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner. This means that for a person to be affected by this syndrome, both copies of the gene in each of their cells must have mutations. In simpler terms, an individual needs to inherit a mutated gene from both parents to develop the condition. Typically, the parents of someone with arterial tortuosity syndrome each carry one copy of the mutated gene.\nWhy this matters: Is arterial tortuosity syndrome inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Arterial tortuosity syndrome is a genetic condition that is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner. This means that for a person to be affected by this syndrome, both copies of the gene in each of their cells must have mutations. In simpler terms, an individual needs to inherit a mutated gene from both parents to develop the condition. Typically, the parents of someone with arterial tortuosity syndrome each carry one copy of the mutated gene.\nWhy this matters: Is arterial tortuosity syndrome inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Arterial tortuosity syndrome is a genetic condition that is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner. This means that for a person to be affected by this syndrome, both copies of the gene in each of their cells must have mutations. In simpler terms, an individual needs to inherit a mutated gene from both parents to develop the condition. Typically, the parents of someone with arterial tortuosity syndrome each carry one copy of the mutated gene.\nWhy this matters: Is arterial tortuosity syndrome inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
