          "id": "medquad-chunk-a98b62e698f0f4ba",
          "title": "What is (are) asphyxiating thoracic dystrophy ?",
          "content": "Asphyxiating thoracic dystrophy, which is also known as Jeune syndrome, is a genetic disorder that significantly impacts the growth of bones in the body. This condition is characterized by a narrow chest, short ribs, and shortened bones in the arms and legs. Additionally, individuals with this syndrome may have extra fingers or toes, a condition referred to as polydactyly. Other skeletal abnormalities associated with asphyxiating thoracic dystrophy can include collarbones and pelvic bones that are shaped unusually, as well as the ends of the long bones in the arms and legs being cone-shaped.\nInfants who are born with asphyxiating thoracic dystrophy often have a very narrow, bell-shaped chest. This unique shape can make it challenging for their lungs to grow and expand properly, which can lead to serious breathing difficulties. Unfortunately, many of these infants may only survive for a short period, typically into infancy or early childhood. However, there is hope for those who manage to survive beyond their early years. For some individuals, the narrow chest and related breathing problems may improve as they grow older, allowing for a better quality of life.\nInterestingly, not everyone with asphyxiating thoracic dystrophy experiences the same severity of symptoms. Some individuals may have milder skeletal abnormalities and only face minor breathing difficulties, such as rapid breathing or shortness of breath. These individuals may be able to live into their teenage years or even adulthood, which can be a positive outcome.\nAs individuals with this condition grow older, they may face additional health challenges. After infancy, there is an increased risk of developing serious kidney problems, which can lead to kidney malfunction or failure. Heart defects are also a concern, as well as a narrowing of the airway, known as subglottic stenosis, which can further complicate breathing.\nIn addition to these issues, there are other less common features associated with asphyxiating thoracic dystrophy. These can include liver disease, the presence of fluid-filled sacs (cysts) in the pancreas, dental abnormalities, and an eye condition called retinal dystrophy, which can potentially lead to vision loss. It is important for individuals with this condition to receive regular medical care and monitoring to address these various health concerns and improve their overall well-being.\nContext recap: Asphyxiating thoracic dystrophy, which is also known as Jeune syndrome, is a genetic disorder that significantly impacts the growth of bones in the body. This condition is characterized by a narrow chest, short ribs, and shortened bones in the arms and legs. Additionally, individuals with this syndrome may have extra fingers or toes, a condition referred to as polydactyly. Other skeletal abnormalities associated with asphyxiating thoracic dystrophy can include collarbones and pelvic bones that are shaped unusually, as well as the ends of the long bones in the arms and legs being cone-shaped.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) asphyxiating thoracic dystrophy ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: Asphyxiating thoracic dystrophy, which is also known as Jeune syndrome, is a genetic disorder that significantly impacts the growth of bones in the body. This condition is characterized by a narrow chest, short ribs, and shortened bones in the arms and legs. Additionally, individuals with this syndrome may have extra fingers or toes, a condition referred to as polydactyly. Other skeletal abnormalities associated with asphyxiating thoracic dystrophy can include collarbones and pelvic bones that are shaped unusually, as well as the ends of the long bones in the arms and legs being cone-shaped.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) asphyxiating thoracic dystrophy ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
