          "id": "medquad-chunk-2a43fe3f22d230ea",
          "title": "What is (are) ataxia with vitamin E deficiency ?",
          "content": "Ataxia with vitamin E deficiency is a health condition that affects how our bodies use vitamin E, an essential nutrient we obtain from the foods we eat. Vitamin E plays a crucial role in our health as it acts as an antioxidant. This means it helps protect our cells from damage caused by harmful substances known as free radicals, which are unstable molecules that can cause harm to our bodies. When someone has a deficiency of vitamin E, it can lead to various neurological issues.\nOne of the main problems associated with this deficiency is ataxia, which refers to difficulties with movement coordination. This means that individuals may find it hard to control their movements, leading to unsteady walking or trouble with balance. Another issue that can arise is dysarthria, which is a condition that affects speech. People with dysarthria may have slurred or slow speech, making it difficult for others to understand them.\nIn addition to these challenges, individuals with ataxia due to vitamin E deficiency may experience lower limb areflexia, which is the loss of reflexes in the legs. This can make it harder to react quickly to situations, such as stumbling or losing balance. Furthermore, they might also experience peripheral neuropathy, which is a reduction in sensation in their hands and feet. This can lead to difficulties in feeling temperature or touch, which can be quite uncomfortable.\nSome individuals with this condition may also develop an eye problem known as retinitis pigmentosa. This condition affects the retina, the part of the eye that helps us see, and can lead to vision loss over time.\nMost people who have ataxia with vitamin E deficiency start to notice movement difficulties between the ages of 5 and 15 years. These challenges often become more pronounced as they grow older, making it important for individuals to seek medical advice and support to manage their symptoms effectively. Early diagnosis and intervention can help improve quality of life and provide strategies to cope with the challenges posed by this condition.\nContext recap: Ataxia with vitamin E deficiency is a health condition that affects how our bodies use vitamin E, an essential nutrient we obtain from the foods we eat. Vitamin E plays a crucial role in our health as it acts as an antioxidant. This means it helps protect our cells from damage caused by harmful substances known as free radicals, which are unstable molecules that can cause harm to our bodies. When someone has a deficiency of vitamin E, it can lead to various neurological issues.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) ataxia with vitamin E deficiency ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Ataxia with vitamin E deficiency is a health condition that affects how our bodies use vitamin E, an essential nutrient we obtain from the foods we eat. Vitamin E plays a crucial role in our health as it acts as an antioxidant. This means it helps protect our cells from damage caused by harmful substances known as free radicals, which are unstable molecules that can cause harm to our bodies. When someone has a deficiency of vitamin E, it can lead to various neurological issues.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) ataxia with vitamin E deficiency ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
          "kind": "concept"
