          "id": "medquad-chunk-88b073fd0379b64a",
          "title": "How many people are affected by atelosteogenesis type 3 ?",
          "content": "Atelosteogenesis type 3 is recognized as a rare genetic disorder, meaning that it affects only a small number of people. The precise number of individuals who have this condition is not clearly established, but research indicates that approximately two dozen people have been diagnosed with it so far. This limited number emphasizes how uncommon this disorder is within the general population, making it an important area of study in medical genetics.\nContext recap: Atelosteogenesis type 3 is recognized as a rare genetic disorder, meaning that it affects only a small number of people. The precise number of individuals who have this condition is not clearly established, but research indicates that approximately two dozen people have been diagnosed with it so far. This limited number emphasizes how uncommon this disorder is within the general population, making it an important area of study in medical genetics.\nContext recap: Atelosteogenesis type 3 is recognized as a rare genetic disorder, meaning that it affects only a small number of people. The precise number of individuals who have this condition is not clearly established, but research indicates that approximately two dozen people have been diagnosed with it so far. This limited number emphasizes how uncommon this disorder is within the general population, making it an important area of study in medical genetics. Context recap: Atelosteogenesis type 3 is recognized as a rare genetic disorder, meaning that it affects only a small number of people.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by atelosteogenesis type 3 ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Atelosteogenesis type 3 is recognized as a rare genetic disorder, meaning that it affects only a small number of people. The precise number of individuals who have this condition is not clearly established, but research indicates that approximately two dozen people have been diagnosed with it so far. This limited number emphasizes how uncommon this disorder is within the general population, making it an important area of study in medical genetics. Context recap: Atelosteogenesis type 3 is recognized as a rare genetic disorder, meaning that it affects only a small number of people.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by atelosteogenesis type 3 ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
          "kind": "concept"
