          "id": "medquad-chunk-66703241f1b23c4c",
          "title": "Is atelosteogenesis type 3 inherited ?",
          "content": "Atelosteogenesis type 3 is a genetic condition that is passed down in an autosomal dominant way. This means that if a person has just one copy of the altered gene in their cells, it is enough to cause the disorder. Interestingly, most cases of atelosteogenesis type 3 happen due to new mutations in the gene. This means that the disorder can appear in individuals who do not have any family history of it. For families, this can be quite surprising, as they might not expect to see this condition if it has not been seen in their relatives before. Understanding this pattern of inheritance is important for families and healthcare providers, as it helps them to better understand the risks and implications of the condition for future generations.\nContext recap: Atelosteogenesis type 3 is a genetic condition that is passed down in an autosomal dominant way. This means that if a person has just one copy of the altered gene in their cells, it is enough to cause the disorder. Interestingly, most cases of atelosteogenesis type 3 happen due to new mutations in the gene. This means that the disorder can appear in individuals who do not have any family history of it.\nWhy this matters: Is atelosteogenesis type 3 inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Atelosteogenesis type 3 is a genetic condition that is passed down in an autosomal dominant way. This means that if a person has just one copy of the altered gene in their cells, it is enough to cause the disorder. Interestingly, most cases of atelosteogenesis type 3 happen due to new mutations in the gene. This means that the disorder can appear in individuals who do not have any family history of it.\nWhy this matters: Is atelosteogenesis type 3 inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: Atelosteogenesis type 3 is a genetic condition that is passed down in an autosomal dominant way. This means that if a person has just one copy of the altered gene in their cells, it is enough to cause the disorder. Interestingly, most cases of atelosteogenesis type 3 happen due to new mutations in the gene. This means that the disorder can appear in individuals who do not have any family history of it.\nWhy this matters: Is atelosteogenesis type 3 inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nGuided check: Ask yourself, \"What is the claim?\", \"Which evidence is strongest?\", and \"What would change my conclusion?\" Use the terms atelosteogenesis, type, means, gene, disorder, condition, medical, inherited while answering to reinforce vocabulary and precision.",
