          "id": "medquad-chunk-fb062083841ecf8e",
          "title": "How many people are affected by autoimmune Addison disease ?",
          "content": "Autoimmune Addison disease is considered a rare condition, impacting approximately 11 to 14 individuals for every 100,000 people of European descent. This means that while it is not very common, it still affects a significant number of people. In developed countries, the autoimmune form of Addison disease is the most frequently observed type, accounting for up to 90 percent of all diagnosed cases. This statistic underscores the importance of raising awareness about the disease, as understanding its prevalence can help in early detection and treatment for those who are affected. By learning more about autoimmune Addison disease, we can better support individuals who live with this condition and contribute to ongoing research efforts aimed at improving their quality of life.\nContext recap: Autoimmune Addison disease is considered a rare condition, impacting approximately 11 to 14 individuals for every 100,000 people of European descent. This means that while it is not very common, it still affects a significant number of people. In developed countries, the autoimmune form of Addison disease is the most frequently observed type, accounting for up to 90 percent of all diagnosed cases. This statistic underscores the importance of raising awareness about the disease, as understanding its prevalence can help in early detection and treatment for those who are affected.\nContext recap: Autoimmune Addison disease is considered a rare condition, impacting approximately 11 to 14 individuals for every 100,000 people of European descent. This means that while it is not very common, it still affects a significant number of people. In developed countries, the autoimmune form of Addison disease is the most frequently observed type, accounting for up to 90 percent of all diagnosed cases. This statistic underscores the importance of raising awareness about the disease, as understanding its prevalence can help in early detection and treatment for those who are affected.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by autoimmune Addison disease ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Autoimmune Addison disease is considered a rare condition, impacting approximately 11 to 14 individuals for every 100,000 people of European descent. This means that while it is not very common, it still affects a significant number of people. In developed countries, the autoimmune form of Addison disease is the most frequently observed type, accounting for up to 90 percent of all diagnosed cases. This statistic underscores the importance of raising awareness about the disease, as understanding its prevalence can help in early detection and treatment for those who are affected.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by autoimmune Addison disease ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
