          "id": "medquad-chunk-5daaf8aed018965d",
          "title": "Is autosomal dominant congenital stationary night blindness inherited ?",
          "content": "Autosomal Dominant Congenital Stationary Night Blindness is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner. This means that having just one copy of the altered gene in each cell is enough to cause the condition. If one parent has the gene mutation, there is a chance that their child may inherit it as well. Understanding this inheritance pattern is important for families, as it can help them assess their risk of passing the condition to their children and guide them in making informed decisions regarding genetic counseling.\nContext recap: Autosomal Dominant Congenital Stationary Night Blindness is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner. This means that having just one copy of the altered gene in each cell is enough to cause the condition. If one parent has the gene mutation, there is a chance that their child may inherit it as well. Understanding this inheritance pattern is important for families, as it can help them assess their risk of passing the condition to their children and guide them in making informed decisions regarding genetic counseling.\nContext recap: Autosomal Dominant Congenital Stationary Night Blindness is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner. This means that having just one copy of the altered gene in each cell is enough to cause the condition. If one parent has the gene mutation, there is a chance that their child may inherit it as well. Understanding this inheritance pattern is important for families, as it can help them assess their risk of passing the condition to their children and guide them in making informed decisions regarding genetic counseling.\nWhy this matters: Is autosomal dominant congenital stationary night blindness inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Autosomal Dominant Congenital Stationary Night Blindness is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner. This means that having just one copy of the altered gene in each cell is enough to cause the condition. If one parent has the gene mutation, there is a chance that their child may inherit it as well. Understanding this inheritance pattern is important for families, as it can help them assess their risk of passing the condition to their children and guide them in making informed decisions regarding genetic counseling.\nWhy this matters: Is autosomal dominant congenital stationary night blindness inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
