          "id": "medquad-chunk-2684118ad04d6087",
          "title": "How many people are affected by autosomal dominant hyper-IgE syndrome ?",
          "content": "Autosomal dominant hyper-IgE syndrome is a very rare condition that affects fewer than one person in every million individuals. This means that it is not commonly seen in the general population, making it a unique health concern.\nContext recap: Autosomal dominant hyper-IgE syndrome is a very rare condition that affects fewer than one person in every million individuals. This means that it is not commonly seen in the general population, making it a unique health concern.\nContext recap: Autosomal dominant hyper-IgE syndrome is a very rare condition that affects fewer than one person in every million individuals. This means that it is not commonly seen in the general population, making it a unique health concern. Context recap: Autosomal dominant hyper-IgE syndrome is a very rare condition that affects fewer than one person in every million individuals. This means that it is not commonly seen in the general population, making it a unique health concern.\nContext recap: Autosomal dominant hyper-IgE syndrome is a very rare condition that affects fewer than one person in every million individuals. This means that it is not commonly seen in the general population, making it a unique health concern. Context recap: Autosomal dominant hyper-IgE syndrome is a very rare condition that affects fewer than one person in every million individuals. This means that it is not commonly seen in the general population, making it a unique health concern.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by autosomal dominant hyper-IgE syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
