          "title": "How many people are affected by Baller-Gerold syndrome ?",
          "content": "Baller-Gerold syndrome is a rare genetic condition that affects individuals in unique ways. Although the exact number of people impacted by this syndrome is not clearly known, it is estimated that it affects fewer than 1 in every million people. This means that it is quite uncommon. In fact, medical literature has documented fewer than 40 cases of this syndrome, which underscores its rarity. The limited number of cases makes it crucial for researchers and healthcare professionals to increase awareness and understanding of Baller-Gerold syndrome. By doing so, they can improve diagnosis and provide better support for those who are affected by this condition. Continued research is essential to uncover more about its characteristics and potential treatments, which can ultimately help individuals and families dealing with this syndrome.\nContext recap: Baller-Gerold syndrome is a rare genetic condition that affects individuals in unique ways. Although the exact number of people impacted by this syndrome is not clearly known, it is estimated that it affects fewer than 1 in every million people. This means that it is quite uncommon. In fact, medical literature has documented fewer than 40 cases of this syndrome, which underscores its rarity.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by Baller-Gerold syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Baller-Gerold syndrome is a rare genetic condition that affects individuals in unique ways. Although the exact number of people impacted by this syndrome is not clearly known, it is estimated that it affects fewer than 1 in every million people. This means that it is quite uncommon. In fact, medical literature has documented fewer than 40 cases of this syndrome, which underscores its rarity.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by Baller-Gerold syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: Baller-Gerold syndrome is a rare genetic condition that affects individuals in unique ways. Although the exact number of people impacted by this syndrome is not clearly known, it is estimated that it affects fewer than 1 in every million people. This means that it is quite uncommon. In fact, medical literature has documented fewer than 40 cases of this syndrome, which underscores its rarity.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by Baller-Gerold syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nGuided check: Ask yourself, \"What is the claim?\", \"Which evidence is strongest?\", and \"What would change my conclusion?\" Use the terms syndrome, people, baller-gerold, medical, affects, fewer, affected, condition while answering to reinforce vocabulary and precision.",
          "kind": "concept"
