          "id": "medquad-chunk-eb9532104cfb2d45",
          "title": "Is Bannayan-Riley-Ruvalcaba syndrome inherited ?",
          "content": "Bannayan-Riley-Ruvalcaba syndrome is inherited in a way known as autosomal dominant inheritance. This means that having just one copy of the altered gene in each cell is enough to cause the disorder. If a parent has the altered gene, there is a chance that their child may inherit it. Understanding this pattern of inheritance is important for families affected by the syndrome, as it can help them make informed decisions about genetic testing and family planning.\nContext recap: Bannayan-Riley-Ruvalcaba syndrome is inherited in a way known as autosomal dominant inheritance. This means that having just one copy of the altered gene in each cell is enough to cause the disorder. If a parent has the altered gene, there is a chance that their child may inherit it. Understanding this pattern of inheritance is important for families affected by the syndrome, as it can help them make informed decisions about genetic testing and family planning.\nContext recap: Bannayan-Riley-Ruvalcaba syndrome is inherited in a way known as autosomal dominant inheritance. This means that having just one copy of the altered gene in each cell is enough to cause the disorder. If a parent has the altered gene, there is a chance that their child may inherit it. Understanding this pattern of inheritance is important for families affected by the syndrome, as it can help them make informed decisions about genetic testing and family planning.\nWhy this matters: Is Bannayan-Riley-Ruvalcaba syndrome inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: Bannayan-Riley-Ruvalcaba syndrome is inherited in a way known as autosomal dominant inheritance. This means that having just one copy of the altered gene in each cell is enough to cause the disorder. If a parent has the altered gene, there is a chance that their child may inherit it. Understanding this pattern of inheritance is important for families affected by the syndrome, as it can help them make informed decisions about genetic testing and family planning.\nWhy this matters: Is Bannayan-Riley-Ruvalcaba syndrome inherited ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
