          "id": "medquad-chunk-12b558e068b0caa6",
          "title": "What are the genetic changes related to Baraitser-Winter syndrome ?",
          "content": "Baraitser-Winter syndrome is a genetic condition that can arise from changes, known as mutations, in two specific genes: ACTB and ACTG1. These genes are crucial because they provide the instructions needed to create two important proteins called beta-actin and gamma-actin. These proteins are found in many types of cells throughout the body and are vital for maintaining the cell's structure and enabling movement.\nThe proteins beta-actin and gamma-actin are part of a larger network called the actin cytoskeleton. You can think of the actin cytoskeleton as the scaffolding of a building; it helps cells keep their shape and supports various functions, including movement. When mutations occur in the ACTB or ACTG1 genes, the production or function of beta-actin and gamma-actin can be affected. This disruption can lead to significant changes in how the actin cytoskeleton is organized, which in turn alters the structure of the cells.\nThese changes can have a wide-ranging impact on the development of the body, especially concerning the movement of nerve cells in the brain. Proper neuronal migration is essential for the brain to develop correctly, and any issues in this process can lead to various symptoms associated with Baraitser-Winter syndrome.\nIndividuals with this syndrome may experience a variety of signs and symptoms, which can include developmental delays, intellectual disabilities, and physical abnormalities. The reason for this diversity in symptoms is that the malfunctioning actin proteins affect many different cellular activities and systems in the body. Since beta-actin and gamma-actin are present in numerous cell types, the consequences of their dysfunction can be widespread, impacting overall health and development. Understanding these genetic changes helps researchers and healthcare professionals provide better support and interventions for individuals affected by Baraitser-Winter syndrome.\nContext recap: Baraitser-Winter syndrome is a genetic condition that can arise from changes, known as mutations, in two specific genes: ACTB and ACTG1. These genes are crucial because they provide the instructions needed to create two important proteins called beta-actin and gamma-actin. These proteins are found in many types of cells throughout the body and are vital for maintaining the cell's structure and enabling movement. The proteins beta-actin and gamma-actin are part of a larger network called the actin cytoskeleton.\nWhy this matters: What are the genetic changes related to Baraitser-Winter syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Baraitser-Winter syndrome is a genetic condition that can arise from changes, known as mutations, in two specific genes: ACTB and ACTG1. These genes are crucial because they provide the instructions needed to create two important proteins called beta-actin and gamma-actin. These proteins are found in many types of cells throughout the body and are vital for maintaining the cell's structure and enabling movement. The proteins beta-actin and gamma-actin are part of a larger network called the actin cytoskeleton.\nWhy this matters: What are the genetic changes related to Baraitser-Winter syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Baraitser-Winter syndrome is a genetic condition that can arise from changes, known as mutations, in two specific genes: ACTB and ACTG1. These genes are crucial because they provide the instructions needed to create two important proteins called beta-actin and gamma-actin. These proteins are found in many types of cells throughout the body and are vital for maintaining the cell's structure and enabling movement. The proteins beta-actin and gamma-actin are part of a larger network called the actin cytoskeleton.\nWhy this matters: What are the genetic changes related to Baraitser-Winter syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
