          "id": "medquad-chunk-2ad517ea4e1c72c4",
          "title": "How many people are affected by Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome ?",
          "content": "Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome is a genetic condition that is estimated to affect about 1 in every 13,700 newborns worldwide. This means that for every 13,700 babies born, one may have this syndrome. However, it is important to note that the actual number of individuals affected could be higher than this estimate. This is because some people may have milder symptoms that do not lead to a diagnosis. This situation emphasizes the need for greater awareness and understanding of Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome. By increasing awareness, we can help ensure that those who might be living with this condition, even without a formal diagnosis, receive the support and care they need. Ongoing research is crucial in identifying and assisting individuals who may be affected by this syndrome, as it can lead to better outcomes and improved quality of life for those impacted.\nContext recap: Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome is a genetic condition that is estimated to affect about 1 in every 13,700 newborns worldwide. This means that for every 13,700 babies born, one may have this syndrome. However, it is important to note that the actual number of individuals affected could be higher than this estimate. This is because some people may have milder symptoms that do not lead to a diagnosis.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome is a genetic condition that is estimated to affect about 1 in every 13,700 newborns worldwide. This means that for every 13,700 babies born, one may have this syndrome. However, it is important to note that the actual number of individuals affected could be higher than this estimate. This is because some people may have milder symptoms that do not lead to a diagnosis.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome is a genetic condition that is estimated to affect about 1 in every 13,700 newborns worldwide. This means that for every 13,700 babies born, one may have this syndrome. However, it is important to note that the actual number of individuals affected could be higher than this estimate. This is because some people may have milder symptoms that do not lead to a diagnosis.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Medical Genetics (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nGuided check: Ask yourself, \"What is the claim?\", \"Which evidence is strongest?\", and \"What would change my conclusion?\" Use the terms syndrome, affected, beckwith-wiedemann, people, every, condition, individuals, lead while answering to reinforce vocabulary and precision.",
